In article <CMwvGv.JMw@dcs.ed.ac.uk> pdc@dcs.ed.ac.uk (Paul Crowley) writes:
  [ given a hash, no way to get information about the input ]
> Does anyone know of a way of defining this more precisely?

Yes. See the FAQ, section 4.2, and analogize.

> Ideally we'd have an encryption algorithm that only used the major
> property of cryptographic message digest functions, namely that it is
> computationally infeasable to generate two messages that collide.

There is no good theoretical or practical reason for this property to
be exalted above all other structural properties of hash functions.

